arch:property.oc:show_val: Small, circular alignment of rocks in the west end of trench, north side. 8/3/2001 After exposing more of the feature, it starts to take on a linear appearance heading N-S. Aug. 18, 2001 This locus turned out to be much more exciting than originally thought. This locus is a cist tomb with a body inside. It extends into the baulk and had rocks overlying the upper portion of the body. The burial for this locus is L6010.

Two large, flat flagstones take up the majority of space. There are several small cobbles between them, plus a sequence of small to large cobbles around the rest of the western flagstone. One of thee looks to be a core with multiple flake scars.

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
